english:
  title: A Record of the Virtuous Life of Sagehood
  author: Park Eun
  language: eng
  text: "When the Sovereign held court, he devoted himself to nurturing talent and cherished the schools, providing ample sustenance and generous dispensations, selecting worthy men as teachers to receive the scholars of all lands. These scholars gathered like clouds in the sacred halls, each urging themselves onward, observing one another in goodness. Some revered him with longing, others were drawn by strength, yet feared still they might be rejected—all spoke his name: Sagehood. When the Sovereign ascended the throne and sought talent, through the second examination Sagehood rose as chief laureate. From ministers and nobles below, all honored his gifts and respected his name, desiring his company yet not daring such familiarity—all called him Master Kim. When he passed, those who knew him grieved; those who did not mourned. All said: \"A good man has departed.\" They sent gifts and provided coffin and shroud for his burial. After the interment, I said to those who had been his companions: \"Sagehood is gone. His tomb bears no inscription, his grave no marker. Will not his virtues and deeds fade into obscurity?\" All agreed. They recounted to me his daily conduct; I gathered what I could learn, and from his kinsman, a clerk of the Bureau of Rites, I learned his age and lineage, obtaining also records of his inner character. Taking what was known of him among men, I have arranged and composed this account for those who come after, that those who hold the brush might draw from it.\n\nHis name was Ch'ŏnnyŏng, of the Kim clan of Kyŏngju. The Kyŏngju Kims descended from the tutor of King Kyŏngsun of Silla. Among his descendants was one who, in the waning days of Koryŏ, aided our Great Founder in establishing the realm and was enfeoffed as Lord of Kyerim. His grandson Chongsun, through pristine virtue, achieved prominence and, upon his death, received the posthumous name Kongho. Kongho's son Chise held many offices, culminating in the position of Magistrate of Hongju. The Magistrate married a daughter of the An clan and begat our subject. It was the year of Kichuk, in the month of Wei, on the day Kyŏngjin. \n\nAt eleven he lost his father; at eighteen his mother. Alone and without recourse, yet possessed of keen brilliance that set him apart. His learning came as natural gift. Early, through poetry and prose, he rose first in the examination for presented scholars and became an upper-dormitory student. With his fellows he prostrated at the palace gate, twice presenting memorials to remonstrate against the court's affairs. Among the literati, his name was often spoken, and his fame grew great. They expected him for high office.\n\nIn the year Pingshen of the Hongji era, when he was twenty-eight, though his rank was not yet low, all who spoke said he was wronged. Those who conducted the examination feared losing him. When he was placed as chief laureate, it was spoken as a blessing for the realm in gaining such talent. That one orphaned in youth, without the support of father and elder brothers, could yet establish himself through diligent study and exceptional writing, never falling behind in examinations—could any achieve this without gifts surpassing ordinary men?\n\nBy regulation he received the post of Keeper of Records at the National Academy, was selected as Assistant Clerk of the Bureau of Personnel while holding the office of Historiographer, participated in compiling the Veritable Records of the Sovereign, and advanced to Reader of the Hall of Mosaic Writing. When made Right Clerk of the Bureau of Revenue, the Bureau of Personnel said his learning merited a place among imperial attendants, not the salt and grain he then held. He was recommended for the post of Reader of the Hall of Letters, and soon advanced to Vice-Instructor. Outwardly he was mild and accommodating; inwardly resolute and decisive. His speech was frank and forthright; his handling of affairs, clean and sharp. When he saw goodness, he feared he could not advocate it; when he saw wrong, he feared he could not oppose it—such was his nature.\n\nWhen the Hall deliberated on affairs of state, gathering various opinions, each man hesitated to speak, holding to agreement and disagreement in caution. But Sagehood would resolve it with a single word, unmoved by idle talk. Those who wished to speak looked to him for weight. Once, with a colleague, he submitted a memorial discussing the advantages and disadvantages of building fortifications on the border, questioning the chief proposer. An inquiry was ordered, but was soon set aside without judgment. Later, when he spoke again on state affairs and displeased the Prime Minister, he was either dismissed or demoted. He was demoted to Examiner of the Hall of Rectification. Following the Envoy to the Celestial Court, he became skilled in the speech of the north. Returning, he became Censor in the Bureau of Censors. At audience, he drew upon classical parallels, citing evidence from past and present, speaking with clarity and precision, avoiding pedantic irrelevance. All his words pleased the royal ear. An aged minister who heard him exchanged knowing glances with his colleagues, whispering: \"A true censorate official.\" Leaving, they spoke without ceasing to their children of his merit.\n\nWhen he fell ill and did not appear at court for several days, the Sovereign asked: \"Why have we not seen Master Kim for so long?\" He requested leave but was not granted it. Instead, he received an imperial decree and medicine. Soon he rose and returned to duty. The Bureau of Personnel thought that if Sagehood remained long in the censorate, the court's discipline might flourish. They promoted him to Censor-in-Chief. He declined twice due to illness, and his request was granted. Yet it was deemed improper to send him outside. He was transferred internally as Direct Rector of the Hall of Letters, and concurrently made Instructor of the Hall of Accumulated Culture. The post of Instructor was not to be held save by one destined for high office. In merely eight years from first receiving office, Sagehood rose nine times, each time to positions of rank. The office of Prime Minister lay within reach. Yet he had always loved simplicity and quiet, ashamed of advancement. With each promotion, his heart grew uneasy. Again, through illness, he resigned from the censorate. Rather than be sent to the provinces, he was transferred within the capital. He sought to decline, but illness prevented him from persisting in this refusal.\n\nIndeed, a name is what scholars pursue; office is what brings men honor. Though these should not come, I would strive for them—how much more should one flee when they come unbidden? Considering Sagehood's heart, is he not one among a thousand?\n\nSagehood lived in great poverty. Throughout his service, all his posts were pure and distinguished. Reaching the rank of Junior Third Rank, he acquired not a single plot of land. His dwelling was his ancestor's modest house, barely holding his wife and children, lacking even walls to mark its bounds, without space for guests. Yet he could still provide for his orphaned younger brother, arranging his marriage in timely fashion. People praised him for this. By now his coffin stood without shelter, his mourning lacked what was needed, and the costs of encoffining and burial were all borne by friends. Thus was Sagehood's virtue made manifest.\n\nIn the first month he fell ill. The sickness deepened and would not heal. By the eighth month, on the day Jiachen, he passed away. In the ninth month, on the day Yiyou, he was buried. The place was the eastern side of the Great Temple Mountain in Koyang, at the Plain of Sŭngbo, some ten paces from the tomb of the Magistrate. He lived thirty-five years—it was the sixteenth year of Hongji, the year Kiyehae. His wife was of the royal clan, daughter of Kim Jŏng, Vice-commander of Myŏngsan. They had five sons and one daughter, the latter not yet of marriageable age, the eldest son but eleven years old. His wet-nurse carried the boy as he wept in his place. The mourners' sorrow deepened.\n\nI, Ŭn, was of Sagehood's examination cohort. When he held office in the Hall of Letters, I served as Compiler. When he was demoted, I too was dismissed. Thus I knew him best. His face was spare and still—to see him was to think one could not approach. Yet in conversation, his speech and laughter flowed gently, making the listener forget weariness. Sometimes, grasping a wine cup, he would discourse on past and present, his spirit vast and open, without constraint or boundary—a true gentleman of generous heart.\n\nI compose this praise: His conduct was not unrefined; the age was not ungrateful; yet fate alone denied him years. To whom then shall we assign blame? To heaven itself? \n\nAlas! That his name was not renowned is the fault of his friends. That a man of such virtue as Sagehood should have his memory lost—is this not the shame of us all? In writing this account, I dare not presume it shall pass to posterity. Those who truly knew Sagehood number but one or two. How can I do him justice? Yet if there be those who know Sagehood and will take up the brush after me, and continue to write, then his deeds shall be fully told and his memory widely spread. I have therefore prepared two copies—one to send to Master Nam Sahwa of Uichun, the other to Master Yi Taekji of Doksui. Both are friends of Sagehood."
  footnotes:
    - The Sovereign (成廟) refers to King Sŏngjong, a great patron of scholarship and meritocratic examination.
    - The 'second examination' (第二科) refers to the civil service examination system, with 'chief laureate' (壯元) being the top rank.
    - Kyerim (鷄林) is an ancient name for the Kyŏngju region, deeply associated with Silla.
    - The 'Hall of Letters' (弘文館) and 'Hall of Accumulated Culture' (藝文館) were prestigious bureaucratic institutions, the former particularly concerned with imperial advisory functions.
    - The reference to eight years and nine promotions illustrates the rapid but troubled rise of an exceptionally talented official whose virtue and integrity prevented him from fully enjoying his advancement.
